article.description:
Chris Bosh tied his career-high with 25 points and Morris Peterson scored a season-high 21 to lead the Toronto Raptors to a 105-94 victory over the slumping Orlando Magic on
Monday night.
article.headline: Orlando loses sixth in a row on road
article.linkText: Bosh, Peterson lead Raptors past Magic
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Chris Bosh acknowledged he's not ready to replace Vince Carter as the Toronto Raptors' main offensive option, though he'd eventually like to. Bosh tied his career-high with 25 points and Morris Peterson scored a season-high 21 to lead Toronto to a 105-94 victory over the slumping Orlando Magic on Monday night. Bosh also had 12 rebounds for the Raptors, who ended a three-game losing skid. The second-year forward matched his career-high for points set Nov. 16, 2003 against Houston. "Not yet," Bosh said when asked if he's ready to assume the role that's been vacant since Carter was traded to New Jersey last month. "It's a little tough. I have my nights. I'm still learning. Every player wants to embrace that, but it's real early." The Raptors are hoping to rebuild around the 20-year-old, but he has struggled at times this season. "We just have to get him to play at this level more consistently," Toronto coach Sam Mitchell said. Peterson thinks Bosh will become a franchise player. The Raptors are 3-5 since trading Carter on Dec. 17. "People don't realize he's only 20 years old, and he's doing a lot of great things," Peterson said. "When you look at guys like Kevin Garnett, and some of the guys that came into the league at his age, he's definitely right up there with those guys at their age, if not better." Steve Francis had 19 points for the Magic, who have lost four straight overall and six in a row on the road. Orlando got off to another slow start, trailing by as many as 16 points in the first half. In their previous three losses they trailed by as many as 19, 11 and 25 in the first half. "If we don't play defense, rebound and not worry about scoring, we will not come of our losing streak, plain and simple," Francis said. Orlando's frustration showed in the fourth quarter when Francis received a late technical and Cuttino Mobley was ejected after getting back-to-back technicals. Bosh had food poisoning when Orlando outrebounded Toronto 61-32 in a 129-108 loss on Dec. 1. This time, Toronto outrebounded Orlando 46-38. It was Francis' turn to complain about bad food. "That's the last time I eat a burger in Canada," Francis said. The Magic cut Toronto's lead to seven in the fourth quarter, but Peterson made a jumper and a 3-pointer to make it 92-80 with 6:54 left. After Francis and Mobley received their technicals, Bosh converted a three-point play to give Toronto a 102-87 lead with 3:08 left. Lamond Murray's 3-pointer made it a 15-point lead with 2:30 remaining. Bosh had 12 points and five rebounds in the first quarter alone.

Game notes
Toronto center Loren Woods began the season as the starting center, but hasn't started the last three games. Rookie Rafael Araujo now starts. Araujo had just four points in four minutes. "When you're losing you have to shake things up," Toronto coach Sam Mitchell said. "We need to see Araujo play. He was our eighth pick." ... Raptors forward Aaron Williams missed the game because of a sprained right ankle. ... Orlando coach Johnny Davis started Kelvin Cato instead of Tony Battie, who has started 14 games. "Kelvin's bigger," Davis said. Cato had 11 points and seven rebounds.
